<main id='main-doc'>
  <section id='What_is_Bologna?' class='main-section'>
    <header class='title'>What is Bologna?</header>
    <article>
      <p>
        Bologna is a cold-cut sausage made of finely minced meat that is cured, cooked, and sometimes smoked. Prime cuts, trimmings, fat, and (more rarely) organ meat may be used. Bologna may be extruded into natural or artificial casings, such as intestine or collagen, but is often served with the casing removed. 
      </p>
      <br>
      <p>
        Bologna - colloquially known as "baloney" - was once the most ubiquitous sandwich meat in the United States, a quintessential lunch staple often placed on white bread and paired simply with mayonnaise and a slice of American cheese. While the word conjurs images of brown paper bags and packed lunches, bologna's use was widespread. Institutions like schools and prisons relied on the inexpensive meat as a source of cheap protein. In the 1990s Americans began to seek out less processed foods and - as a result - bologna sales steadily decreased year over year.
      </p>
    </article>
  </section>

  <section id='Origins' class='main-section'>
    <header class='title'>Origins</header>
    <article>     
      <p>
        The roots of modern bologna can be traced back to the mortadella sausage originating from the Emilia-Romagna region of northern Italy. In fact, bologna takes its name from the region's capital of Bologna.
      </p>
      <br>
      <p>
        Mortadella translates to "mortar-ground sausage" in reference to the traditional method of grinding the pork filling into paste with a mortar. As with bologna, mortadella is also a <em>salume</em>, or cured cold-cut, that contains finely ground meat. Where bologna can contain a variety of meats and is uniform in texture, mortadella is made solely of pork and contains cubes of cooked pork fat that give it a marbled appearance.
      </p>
      <br>
      <!--  This code is being used to display recipes to meet project requirements  -->
      <code>
        <h3 class='recipeTitle'> Mortadella di Bologna </h3>
        <div class='recipeWrap'>   
          <table class='recipe'>
